Lab 4

In this lab we build a data.frame to represent a standard deck of 52 playing cards.
It should have 52 rows and one column for each characteristic of a playing card:

  • color \(\in\) {"black", "red"}
  • suit \(\in\) {"clubs", "spades", "diamonds", "hearts" }
  • name \(\in\) {"ace", "2", "3", ..., "king"}
  • rank \(\in\) {1,2,3, ..., 12,13}
  • value \(\in\) {1,2,3, ..., 9,10,10,10,10 }.

For more information or clarity, see here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_52-card_deck

Building deck52

  1. (10 points) Clean. Stylish.

  2. Build the vector color first. It should have 52 elements. Build it like this: color = [red 13 times, black 13 times, red 13 times, black 13 times] . Useful commands are c() and rep().

  3. Build a vector with 52 elements for each of the other four columns: suit, name, rank, value.

  4. (20 points) Use data.frame() to combine the columns into a single data.frame called deck52. Confirm that your data.frame has 52 rows and 5 columns. Make sure it represents an actual deck of cards; check the image to be sure. Run names(deck52) <- toupper(names(deck52)) to convert the column names to upper case.

Extracting events

Consider selecting a card at random from a standard deck. The sample space \(\Omega\) can be represented by deck52. Each row of deck52 represents a possible outcome and has probability = 1/52. An event is any subset of \(\Omega\), so any event corresponds to a set of rows in deck52. Below we define some examples of events associated with this experiment.

Let \(B\) = the event that the selected card is black.

Let \(R\) = the event that the selected card is red.

Let \(D\) = the event that SUIT of the selected card is diamonds, and let \(H, S, C\) define the same event for the other three suits.

Let \(FACE\) = the event that card is a face card = {jack, queen, king}.

Let \(A\) = the event that the card is an ace.

Let \(ODD\) = the event that the VALUE of the card is odd.

Let \(LOW\) = the event that the RANK of the card is less than 3.

  1. (10 points) For each event above, extract and display the corresponding rows of deck52. Use subset or use the filter function from the package dplyr (loaded above). Heres the first one:
B <- filter(deck52, COLOR == 'black') # extracting the event B
B                                     # displaying the subsetted dataframe B

Computing probabilities

Calculate the probabilities below using R. The first one is an example.

  1. \(P(H) =\) __________ . It helps to work it out with a pencil first: \(P(H) = \frac{13 \ hearts}{52 \ cards} = \frac{1}{4}\). How do we get 13/52 in R? To get the 13 use dim(H)[1] or nrow(H). To get the 52 use dim(deck52)[1] or nrow(deck52). Then divide 13/52 to get the answer, 0.25.
H <- filter(deck52, SUIT == 'hearts') # extracting the event H, part of previous question
p_H <- nrow(H) / nrow(deck52)
p_H # display the answer

  1. \(P(FACE)\)

  2. \(P(ODD)\)

  3. \(P(EVEN)\). This is one minus previous answer, but dont solve it that way. Extract the rows where value is even, count them, and divide by 52.

  4. \(P(ODD^C)\). Same as previous problem, but solve it explicitly: extract the rows that are NOT odd, count, divide.

  5. \(P(D)\).

  6. \(P(D \cap R)\). Intersection means AND which is \(\&\) in R.

  7. \(P(D | R)\).

  8. \(P(D \cup R)\). Union means OR which is \(|\) in R. Note that this is unrelated to the \(|\) used in conditional probability.

  9. \(P(F | EVEN)\).

  10. (30 points) Package your probability answers in a 10x3 data.frame called myprobs. Run myprobs <- data.frame(question = '6', probability = 'P(H)', answer = p_H) to see the first row as an example. Attach new rows with rbind(). When the data.frame is complete, run myprobs to display it. Dont use View().
